{"id":"zeal","term":"Zeal","source":"Easton's Bible Dictionary (M.G. Easton, 1897)","html":"<p>An earnest temper; may be enlightened (<a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Numbers 25:11\">Num. 25:11-13</a>; <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"2 Corinthians 7:11\">2 Cor. 7:11</a>; <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"2 Corinthians 9:2\">9:2</a>), or ignorant and misdirected (<a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Romans 10:2\">Rom. 10:2</a>; <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Philippians 3:6\">Phil. 3:6</a>). As a Christian grace, it must be grounded on right principles and directed to right ends (<a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Galatians 4:18\">Gal. 4:18</a>). It is sometimes ascribed to God (<a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"2 Kings 19:31\">2 Kings 19:31</a>; <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Isaiah 9:7\">Isa. 9:7</a>; <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Isaiah 37:32\">37:32</a>; <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Ezekiel 5:13\">Ezek. 5:13</a>).</p>\n\u0000","refs":["Numbers 25:11","2 Corinthians 7:11","2 Corinthians 9:2","Romans 10:2","Philippians 3:6","Galatians 4:18","2 Kings 19:31","Isaiah 9:7","Isaiah 37:32","Ezekiel 5:13"]}